bib_record.title: The reaction Ca-40(a,p)Sc-43 with alpha particles of maximum energy 20 MeV.

free_txt: The detector was an ionization chamber filled
with argon to a pressure of 10 atm and with a very
small admixture of methane. The gas was continuously
circulated over hot calcium. The chamber was of the
fast electron collecting type, and it was provided
with a Frisch grid. The entrance window was an
aluminium coated Mylar foil supported by a disk of
stainless steel with 85 holes of 1 mm diameter; in
thickness it was equivalent to 1.4 mg/cm2 aluminium.
A proportional counter was inserted in front
of the ionization chamber to provide a means of
distinguishing between alpha particles and protons.
Proportional counter  in most experiments was replaced
by a set of anti-scattering slits.

The target foil was a layer of natural calcium (96.9%
Ca-40) evaporated in vacuum from a strip of tungsten
onto a 0.16 mg/cm2 gold foil. The target was carried to
the scattering chamber without being exposed to air.
The thickness of the calcium layer was about
0.65 mg/cm2 for the thickest target.
